The allegations must be thoroughly investigated and where there is evidence of any entities or individuals regardless of their position breaking the law they must be prosecuted she asserted. Over the past few years toxic allegations of impropriety at state-owned enterprises have had a profoundly negative effect on the mood of our country and perceptions of our democratically elected government. We cannot allow political and business competition afflicting the boards (the accounting authorities of state owned enterprises) and the executive management of our state owned enterprises to negate the good work that these companies do. Or to erode the transformation path that South Africa is on Brown warned. Nor should we allow negative narratives to negate the fact that Eskom's turnaround is under way; that it reported a decent profit this year; that loadshedding is slipping into memory even as more people and businesses are connected to the electricity grid she added.